<TITLE> Top Pakistan journalist says Islamabad should be sorry </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 22 (bdnews24.com)  Pakistan journalist Hamid Mir has said Islamabad should be ashamed of its "past deeds" against Dhaka during the 1952 Language Movement and seek forgiveness from the Bangladeshi people. Mir, a columnist, editor and TV anchor, was speaking at a discussion meeting organised by the Bangladesh High Commission in Islamabad on Sunday to mark Amar Ekushey, or February 21, the high commission said in a statement. He highlighted the logical grounds for the Language Movement in what was then East Pakistan, now Bangladesh. Bangladesh commemorates Feb 21 for the sacrifice made by the Language Movement martyrs, students who gave their lives on that day in 1952 for the right to have Bangla as a state language. The day is now observed around the world as International Mother Language Day. Acting Bangladeshi ambassador Md Mahfuzur Rahman and Pakistani media personality Ijaj Gul were among those who spoke on the occasion. The high commission hoisted the national flag half-mast on the day
